1
00:00:02.100 --> 00:00:04.700
In this lesson,
you will start with the simplest form

2
00:00:04.700 --> 00:00:06.933
of agentic RAG, a router.

3
00:00:06.933 --> 00:00:07.800
Given a query,

4
00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:11.033
the router will pick one of several
query entrants to execute a query.

5
00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:14.100
You'll build a simple router
over a single document

6
00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:17.200
that can handle both question
answering as well as summarization.

7
00:00:18.133 --> 00:00:20.233
Let's dive in.

8
00:00:20.233 --> 00:00:23.033
Given a query,
the router will pick one of several

9
00:00:23.033 --> 00:00:25.200
query engines to execute a query.

10
00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:28.333
So this gives you some dynamic
query understanding capabilities.

11
00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:33.000
We'll show you how to build a very
simple router over a single document

12
00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:35.233
that can handle both question answering,

13
00:00:35.233 --> 00:00:37.300
as well as summarization
over that document.

14
00:00:37.300 --> 00:00:38.733
The first three lessons show

15
00:00:38.733 --> 00:00:41.733
you how to build a drone
to capabilities over a single document.

16
00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:44.900
And the last lesson we'll show you
how to build a multi-document agent.

17
00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:47.100
So let's get started.

18
00:00:47.100 --> 00:00:50.933
The first thing we'll do
is to import, our OpenAI key.

19
00:00:50.933 --> 00:00:53.500
And to do this
we'll define a helper function.

20
00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:57.933
Next we need to import
a special module called nest_asyncio.

21
00:00:58.900 --> 00:00:59.733
The reason for this

22
00:00:59.733 --> 00:01:02.733
is that Jupiter runs
an event loop behind the scenes,

23
00:01:02.733 --> 00:01:06.233
and a lot of our modules use async
and to make async play nice

24
00:01:06.233 --> 00:01:08.733
with Jupiter notebooks,
We need to import this.

25
00:01:08.733 --> 00:01:11.733
The next step in terms of setup
is to load in a sample document.

26
00:01:12.233 --> 00:01:15.700
Here we use Meta GPT, a recently accepted
oral paper

27
00:01:15.733 --> 00:01:19.700
Eichler 2024 on a cool new multi-page
framework.

28
00:01:20.233 --> 00:01:22.833
You should definitely check out the paper
if you're interested or

29
00:01:22.833 --> 00:01:26.000
if you're interested in uploading your own
documents, please feel free to do so.

30
00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:30.300
Next we'll import the sentence splitter
from LlamaIndex

31
00:01:30.333 --> 00:01:34.133
The next piece here is we are going to use
our simple directory reader

32
00:01:34.133 --> 00:01:39.133
module and LlamaIndex to read in this PDF
into a parse document representation.

33
00:01:40.733 --> 00:01:42.100
In order to split

34
00:01:42.100 --> 00:01:46.733
these documents into even sized chunks,
and we'll split on the order of sentences.

35
00:01:47.133 --> 00:01:50.000
So we set the trunk size to 1024.

36
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:51.200
And we call splitter dot.

37
00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:54.200
Get nodes from documents
to split these documents into nodes.

38
00:01:55.900 --> 00:01:57.200
Next step is optional.

39
00:01:57.200 --> 00:02:00.433
And this allows us to find an outline
and embedding model.

40
00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:03.933
And you can do this
by specifying a global config setting

41
00:02:03.933 --> 00:02:06.333
where you specify the alignment
and embedding model

42
00:02:06.333 --> 00:02:08.533
that you want to inject
as part of the global config.

43
00:02:08.533 --> 00:02:13.133
By default, we use 3.5 turbo and tex
embedding to oh two in this course.

44
00:02:13.466 --> 00:02:16.233
But of course this allows you
to have the groundwork

45
00:02:16.233 --> 00:02:19.233
to basically inject your own LLMs
as well as embeddings.

46
00:02:20.733 --> 00:02:23.233
So we define the settings
object and settings.llm=OpenAI

47
00:02:23.233 --> 00:02:27.833
and settings.embed_model=OpenAI.

48
00:02:27.833 --> 00:02:28.233
Embedding.

49
00:02:29.533 --> 00:02:32.533
Now we're
ready to start building some indexes.

50
00:02:32.633 --> 00:02:35.733
Here we define two indexes over these
nodes.

51
00:02:36.333 --> 00:02:39.433
This includes
both a summary index and a vector index.

52
00:02:39.933 --> 00:02:44.033
A refresher is that we can think of an
index as a set of metadata over our data.

53
00:02:44.533 --> 00:02:46.966
You can query an index at different
indexes

54
00:02:46.966 --> 00:02:49.966
will have different retrieval behaviors.

55
00:02:50.033 --> 00:02:52.666
A vector index, for instance,
indexes nodes via

56
00:02:52.666 --> 00:02:55.833
text embeddings
and its core abstraction and LlamaIndex,

57
00:02:55.833 --> 00:02:58.833
and a core abstraction
for building any sort of RAG system.

58
00:02:59.266 --> 00:03:01.066
Querying a vector index will return

59
00:03:01.066 --> 00:03:04.966
the most similar nodes
by embedding similarity. A summary index,

60
00:03:04.966 --> 00:03:07.533
on the other hand,
is also a very simple index,

61
00:03:07.533 --> 00:03:10.966
but querying it will return all the nodes
currently in the index,

62
00:03:11.266 --> 00:03:14.266
so it doesn't necessarily
depend on the user query,

63
00:03:14.333 --> 00:03:17.333
but will return all the nodes
that's currently in the index.

64
00:03:18.833 --> 00:03:21.066
To set up both the summary and factor
index.

65
00:03:21.066 --> 00:03:24.066
It's a matter of importing these two
simple models.

66
00:03:29.133 --> 00:03:29.766
Now let's

67
00:03:29.766 --> 00:03:33.266
turn these indexes into query engines
and then query tools.

68
00:03:34.133 --> 00:03:38.433
Each query engine represents, overall
query interface over the data

69
00:03:38.433 --> 00:03:42.633
that's stored in this index, and combines
retrieval with LLM synthesis.

70
00:03:43.266 --> 00:03:46.166
Each query engine is good
for a certain type of question,

71
00:03:46.166 --> 00:03:50.133
and this is a great use case for a router,
which can route dynamically between

72
00:03:50.133 --> 00:03:51.833
these different query entrants.

73
00:03:51.833 --> 00:03:55.966
A query tool now is just the query engine
with metadata, specifically

74
00:03:55.966 --> 00:03:58.966
a description of what types of questions
the tool can answer.

75
00:04:01.133 --> 00:04:03.033
So here we define the summary query

76
00:04:03.033 --> 00:04:06.033
engine equals
summary indexed as query engine.

77
00:04:06.333 --> 00:04:09.633
And then also a vector query engine equals
vector index.

78
00:04:10.533 --> 00:04:14.566
We can see that the query engine
is derived from the each of the indexes.

79
00:04:14.666 --> 00:04:18.733
We can see that for the summary query
engine we set use async equals true to

80
00:04:18.733 --> 00:04:22.833
basically enforce faster query generation
by leveraging async capabilities.

81
00:04:24.333 --> 00:04:25.033
Next a

82
00:04:25.033 --> 00:04:28.033
query tool is just the query engine
with metadata.

83
00:04:28.233 --> 00:04:32.133
It's specifically a description of what
types of questions the tool can answer.

84
00:04:32.933 --> 00:04:35.833
And we'll define a query tool
for both the summary

85
00:04:35.833 --> 00:04:38.833
and vector query engines.

86
00:04:38.866 --> 00:04:41.733
Through this code snippet right here,
you see that the summary tool

87
00:04:41.733 --> 00:04:45.266
description is useful for summarization
questions related to Meta GPT

88
00:04:46.033 --> 00:04:49.833
and the vector tool description is useful
for retrieving specific context

89
00:04:49.833 --> 00:04:52.833
from the Meta GPT paper.

90
00:04:54.933 --> 00:04:55.833
Now that we have

91
00:04:55.833 --> 00:04:58.866
our query engines and tools,
we're ready to define our router.

92
00:04:59.166 --> 00:05:00.233
LlamaIndex provides

93
00:05:00.233 --> 00:05:03.733
several different types of selectors
to enable you to build a router.

94
00:05:04.133 --> 00:05:07.133
And each of these selectors
has distinct attributes.

95
00:05:07.233 --> 00:05:11.233
The LLM selector is one option,
and it involves prompting an LLM

96
00:05:11.233 --> 00:05:13.666
to output a json that is then parsed

97
00:05:13.666 --> 00:05:16.333
and then the corresponding
indexes are queried.

98
00:05:16.333 --> 00:05:19.333
Another option
is to use our pydantic selectors

99
00:05:19.633 --> 00:05:22.433
instead of directly
prompting the LLM with text,

100
00:05:22.433 --> 00:05:27.033
we actually use the function calling APIs
supported by models like OpenAI,

101
00:05:27.233 --> 00:05:31.233
to produce pydantic selection objects,
rather than parsing raw json.

102
00:05:31.533 --> 00:05:33.333
For each of these types of selectors,

103
00:05:33.333 --> 00:05:36.333
we also have the dynamic capabilities
to let you select

104
00:05:36.333 --> 00:05:39.333
one index to route two,
or actually multiple.

105
00:05:39.433 --> 00:05:43.866
Let's try an LLM unpowered single selector
called LLM single selector.

106
00:05:45.733 --> 00:05:47.266
So we import two modules.

107
00:05:47.266 --> 00:05:50.933
We import a router query engine
as well as the LLM single selector.

108
00:05:51.966 --> 00:05:55.333
You see that the router query
engine takes in a selector type

109
00:05:55.466 --> 00:05:58.466
as well as a set of query engine tools.

110
00:05:58.533 --> 00:06:01.533
The selector type you see
is just the LLM single selector,

111
00:06:01.533 --> 00:06:05.466
which means that it prompts the LLM,
makes a single selection, and the query

112
00:06:05.466 --> 00:06:08.733
engine tools include the summarization
tool, as well as the vector tool.

113
00:06:11.033 --> 00:06:14.033
Now let's try testing out some queries.

114
00:06:14.366 --> 00:06:16.766
The first question we'll ask is
"what is a summary

115
00:06:16.766 --> 00:06:19.766
of the document?"

116
00:06:21.933 --> 00:06:23.333
The verbose output allows us

117
00:06:23.333 --> 00:06:26.333
to view the intermediate steps
that are being taken.

118
00:06:26.366 --> 00:06:30.233
We see that the output includes
selecting query engine zero.

119
00:06:30.433 --> 00:06:33.633
Useful for summarization questions
related to Meta GPT.

120
00:06:34.266 --> 00:06:36.633
This means that the first option,
the summary tool,

121
00:06:36.633 --> 00:06:39.633
is actually picked in order to help
answer this question.

122
00:06:40.033 --> 00:06:42.833
And as a result, you're able to get back
a response.

123
00:06:42.833 --> 00:06:45.166
The document introduces Meta GPT,

124
00:06:45.166 --> 00:06:48.333
a metaprogramming framework for LLM
based multi-agent collaboration.

125
00:06:49.333 --> 00:06:51.966
And this
gives an overall summary of the paper

126
00:06:51.966 --> 00:06:54.966
and is synthesize
over all the context in the paper.

127
00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:57.800
So the response comes with sources.

128
00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:01.733
And to inspect the sources, we can take
a look at response dot source nodes.

129
00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:04.600
When we take a look
at the length of response

130
00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:07.600
dot source nodes,
we see that the length is equal to 34.

131
00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:11.400
Coincidentally, this is exactly equal
to the number of chunks

132
00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:13.000
of the entire document.

133
00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:16.100
And so we see that the summary query
engine must have been getting called,

134
00:07:16.433 --> 00:07:20.500
because the summary query on trunk returns
all the trunks corresponding to

135
00:07:20.533 --> 00:07:21.900
the items within its index.

136
00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.200
Let's take a look at another example.

137
00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:28.900
We'll ask the question: "How do agents
share information with other agents?"

138
00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:32.333
So let's ask this
against the overall router query engine

139
00:07:32.733 --> 00:07:36.133
and take a look at both the verbose output
as well as the response.

140
00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:39.400
Here, we see that we actually select query

141
00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:43.200
engine one,
and LLM gives some reasoning as to

142
00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:46.600
why actually pick the vector search tool
as opposed to the summary tool.

143
00:07:47.233 --> 00:07:51.300
It's because the focus is on retrieving
specific context from the Meta GPT paper,

144
00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:55.633
where, agents sharing information
with other agents is probably located

145
00:07:55.633 --> 00:07:57.200
within a paragraph of that paper.

146
00:07:57.200 --> 00:08:00.933
And you see that it's able to find
that context and generate a response. You'll be able

147
00:08:00.933 --> 00:08:04.200
to utilize a shared message for where
they can publish structured messages.

148
00:08:05.900 --> 00:08:06.233
And that

149
00:08:06.233 --> 00:08:09.900
basically helps to conclude lesson
one. To put everything together,

